<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-07-06T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-07-06T19:00:00-05:00" n="157" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d157">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102 Kulangsu/188: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Dooman</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-07-06T20:00:00-04:00">July 6, 1939—8
                                    p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>184. Your 293, June 23, 3 p.m., and Amoy’s 64, July 2, noon, and 66,
                                July 5, 3 p.m. As 2 weeks have elapsed since you left your informal
                                memorandum at the Foreign Office, it would seem that there has been
                                sufficient time for Sawada to familiarize himself with the situation
                                and give you a reply. The Department accordingly suggests that, in
                                your discretion, you make another approach to the Foreign Office in
                                this matter.</p>
                            <p>Repeated to Chungking and Amoy.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>